05567nam a22009375i 9781531500177DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815315001777 a10.1515/97815315001772doi  a(DE-B1597)624073  a(OCoLC)1338642574  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aB105.I47 7aART0090002bisacsh04a128/.3223/eng/202208221 aWeigel, Sigrid, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGrammatology of Images :bA History of the A-Visible /cSigrid Weigel. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b71 b/w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCommonalities00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tNote to the English-Language Edition -- tList of Figures -- tIntroduction: Toward a Grammatology of Images -- t1 The Trace and the Current Revaluation of Lines -- t2 Faces: Between Trace and Image, Encoding and Measurement -- t3 Indexical Images: Trace, Resemblance, and Code -- t4 Effigiēs: Double, Representation, and the Supplementary Economy of the Likeness (Ebenbild) -- t5 Defamatory Images: Disfiguration in Physiognomy and Caricature’s Two Bodies -- t6 Cult Images: Iconoclastic Controversy, the Desire for Images, and the Dialectic of Secularization -- t7 Angels: Images of Making-Appearance between Religion, Art, and Science -- t8 Perspectives of the Grammatology of Images beyond Visual Culture -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGrammatology of Images radically alters how we approach images. Instead of asking for the history, power, or essence of images, Sigrid Weigel addresses imaging as such. The book considers how something a-visible gets transformed into an image. Weigel scrutinizes the moment of mis-en-apparition, of making an appearance, and the process of concealment that accompanies any imaging.Weigel reinterprets Derrida’s and Freud’s concept of the trace as that which must be thought before something exists. In doing so, she illuminates the threshold between traces and iconic images, between something immaterial and its pictorial representation. Chapters alternate between general accounts of the line, the index, the effigy, and the cult-image, and case studies from the history of science, art, politics, and religion, involving faces as indicators of emotion, caricatures as effigies of defamation, and angels as embodiments of transcendental ideas.Weigel’s approach to images illuminates fascinating, unexpected correspondences between premodern and contemporary image-practices, between the history of religion and the modern sciences, and between things that are and are not understood as art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aImage (Philosophy). 4aArt & Visual Culture. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh  aImage.  aangel.  acaricature.  acult image.  aeffigy.  aface.  aimaging.  aindexical image.  atrace, line.1 aSmith, Chadwick Truscott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Architecture and Design 2022z9783110992793oZDB-23-DAD08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2022 Englishz978311099281608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311075166640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781531500177?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttp